from collections import deque

class MyStack:

    def __init__(self):
        self.q = deque()

    def push(self, x: int) -> None:
        self.q.append(x)
        for _ in range(len(self.q) - 1):
            self.q.append(self.q.popleft())

    def pop(self) -> int:
        return self.q.popleft()

    def top(self) -> int:
        return self.q[0]

    def empty(self) -> bool:
        return not self.q
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: push O(n), pop O(1), top O(1), empty O(1)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a single queue and rotates it after each push so the newest element is always at the front, enabling O(1) pop/top. This meets the follow-up requirement of one queue while keeping energy usage low due to minimal extra operations.

